# Per-user configuration — template

Copy this file to `config/user.md` and fill in the values. The copy
is **gitignored**, so your local preferences never land in a commit:

```bash
cp config/user.md.example config/user.md
$EDITOR config/user.md
```

The skills read both this file and
[`active-project.md`](active-project.md) on every invocation. Fields
you leave at the placeholder value are treated as *"ask at runtime"*;
fields you fill in let the skills skip the corresponding prompt. See
[`README.md`](README.md) in this directory for the full tutorial and
the model explainer.

## Identity

```yaml
identity:
  # Your GitHub handle — used to recognise your own drafts / tracker
  # comments so skills do not propose replying to yourself, and to
  # render @-mentions when a skill wants to credit you on a comment.
  github_handle: <your-github-handle>

  # The email address you send security@ replies from. Used by sync
  # and import skills to detect when a thread reply is from you vs.
  # from a teammate or the reporter.
  email: <you@example.com>
```

## Role flags

```yaml
role_flags:
  # PMC membership of the active project. Affects:
  #   - allocate-cve: PMC members get the self-service allocation
  #     recipe (click the URL, paste the title, hit Allocate);
  #     non-PMC users get a relay recipe they forward to a PMC member.
  #   - Any future skill that needs to decide between PMC-gated and
  #     relay flows.
  # If unsure, check the active project's PMC page (for Airflow,
  # https://projects.apache.org/committee.html?airflow).
  # Valid values: true | false.
  pmc_member: false
```

## Tool preferences

The active project declares which capabilities it needs in its
manifest's *Tools enabled* table — for Airflow, see
[`../projects/airflow/project.md`](../projects/airflow/project.md#tools-enabled).
For each capability, set the implementation **you** have configured
locally. Capabilities with only one supported implementation today
(GitHub issue tracking, Vulnogram CVE tool) should stay at the
default — the knob exists so the same `user.md` keeps working when
alternative implementations land.

```yaml
tools:
  # Issue tracker: which tool this user queries for tracker state.
  # Supported today: github.
  issue_tracker: github

  # Inbound email (primary): how this user reads the project's
  # security list. Supported today:
  #   gmail   — Gmail MCP against a personal Gmail account subscribed
  #             to security@<project>.apache.org. This is also the
  #             only tool that can create draft replies — keep it set
  #             even when PonyMail MCP is also enabled below, because
  #             the skills always compose reporter-facing drafts via
  #             Gmail regardless of which read backend answered the
  #             originating query.
  inbound_email: gmail

  # PonyMail MCP (opt-in, primary for reads when enabled): a read-only
  # backend backed by the rbowen/ponymail-mcp server and ASF LDAP
  # OAuth. **When enabled and authenticated, PonyMail MCP becomes the
  # primary read path** for archive queries; Gmail stays as the
  # fallback when PonyMail is disabled, unauthenticated, or the
  # relevant private list is not in this user's allowlist. Gmail
  # also remains the **only** backend that can create drafts, so the
  # skills always compose reporter-facing replies via Gmail
  # regardless of which read backend answered the originating query.
  #
  # Why PonyMail-primary for reads: the archive is authoritative (it
  # sees every message that reached the list, independent of the
  # triager's personal subscription), consistent across team members
  # (two different triagers running the same skill see the same
  # result set), and reaches further back than a typical Gmail
  # mailbox window. Gmail is faster for just-arrived mail (PonyMail
  # archive may lag by minutes), so it remains the right tool for
  # *inbox* use cases but not for *archive* use cases.
  #
  # Setup and operation catalogue live in tools/ponymail/tool.md
  # and tools/ponymail/operations.md respectively.
  ponymail:
    # Whether PonyMail MCP is configured in this user's Claude Code
    # MCP registry (mcpServers.ponymail). When false (the default),
    # skills skip every PonyMail path and run Gmail-only; no blocker
    # is raised and no behavioural change is visible — PonyMail is
    # purely opt-in.
    enabled: false

    # Private mailing lists the user's ASF LDAP account grants
    # archive access to. Skills use this list to decide whether a
    # private-list PonyMail query is worth attempting from this
    # user's session. For a list not in this allowlist, skills fall
    # back to Gmail for that specific list while keeping PonyMail
    # primary for every other list the user can read. An empty list
    # means "public lists only via PonyMail; private lists via
    # Gmail".
    #
    # Expected values for an Airflow security-team PMC member:
    #   - security@airflow.apache.org
    #   - private@airflow.apache.org
    # Non-PMC triagers typically have no private-list LDAP access and
    # leave this empty.
    private_lists: []

  # CVE tool: the CNA tool the release manager pushes CVE records to.
  # Supported today: vulnogram (ASF-hosted).
  cve_tool: vulnogram
```

## Environment paths

```yaml
environment:
  # Absolute path to your local apache/airflow clone. Used by
  # fix-security-issue Step 3 to write code changes locally without
  # asking you every time. There is no default and no auto-detection
  # — filesystem layouts vary per user and a wrong guess masks a
  # misconfigured clone — so if you leave this blank the skill will
  # prompt you at runtime and offer to save your answer back here.
  # Examples: /Users/alice/src/apache-airflow,
  #           /home/bob/work/airflow
  upstream_clone:

  # Optional: the name of the git remote pointing at your fork of
  # apache/airflow. gh pr create uses this to push the fix branch.
  # Leave blank to let the skill detect the first non-origin remote.
  upstream_fork_remote:
```

## Skill defaults

```yaml
skill_defaults:
  # How many days back import-security-issue scans the security list
  # on a vanilla "import new reports" invocation. Can always be
  # overridden per-call (e.g. "import all" = 90d). Default: 30d.
  import_window: 30d

  # Whether to opt into bulk mode for sync-security-issue ("sync all")
  # without an extra prompt. Default: false (ask each time).
  sync_bulk_mode: false
```

## Notes

Free-form. Anything else an agent should remember about how you like
to work on this repo. Examples:

- *"Always surface CVE tool links as markdown, never bare URLs."*
- *"I am on European time; expect morning triage around 09:00 CET."*
- *"I prefer single-scope PRs; split provider-bundle work into one PR
  per provider."*
- *"When a sync turns up a stale draft, include the draft's `From:`
  sender in the flag — I maintain several drafts in parallel."*

```text
(your notes here)
```
